articles.author: Hackster.io
articles.title: A New, More Efficient "Deep-Blue" OLED Could Boost Brightness and Lifespan in Future Displays - Hackster.io
articles.description: Researchers from the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology and Shanghai University have developed a new blue organic light-emitting diode (OLED) that uses "exciplex" to set a record in external quantum efficiency. The "exciplex strategy" revolves around a new molecule type with carbazole and triazine fragments linked by a silicon atom. The team's prototype OLEDs offer a 20.35% external quantum efficiency, which translates to a 5,000 candela per square meter luminance. The team's work has been published in the journal Science Advances, but there is no word yet on a timescale for commercialization in mass-produced OLED displays.

articles.author: LiFO
articles.title: Research: Exercise can cause stroke - In which people - LiFO
articles.description: A new scientific study published in the "Physics of Fluids" journal highlights the danger of acute exercise for patients with particularly blocked carotid arteries. The increased heart rate can cause a stroke in some cases. The researchers used a specialized computational model to simulate blood flow in the carotid arteries in three stages of stenosis, without obstruction, with mild obstruction of 30%, and with moderate obstruction of 50%. They compared the effect of exercise-induced heart rate of 140 beats per minute with resting heart rates of 67 and 100 beats per minute. Exercise improved the health of the simulated carotid artery for healthy and mild cases, but the results for moderate stenosis were concerning. The authors recommend regular monitoring of arterial health for individuals who engage in intense exercise and a carefully prescribed exercise program for individuals with moderate to severe stenosis or a history of stroke.

articles.author: Mirage News
articles.title: New Embryonic Cell Type Self-Destructs to Shield Embryo - Mirage News
articles.description: Scientists studying gene activity data of the early human embryo have discovered a type of cell that self-destructs within days of forming, as part of a quality control process to protect the developing fetus. These cells contain "jumping genes" that can cause damage to DNA, and their descendants undergo programmed cell death. This process appears to be a form of quality control, selecting between cells in favor of the good ones. The findings could help improve IVF or regenerative medicine treatments.

articles.author: Xataka
articles.title: We knew that Jupiter was plagued with storms. NASA has captured one of its ghostly rays - Xataka
articles.description: The NASA spacecraft Juno has captured an image of a green lightning bolt in Jupiter's atmosphere during its 31st flyby of the planet. The image was taken by the JunoCam instrument and processed by scientist Kevin M. Gill. Jupiter's lightning is different from Earth's as it originates in ammonia and water clouds and is mainly detected near the poles. Juno has flown over Jupiter 51 times since its launch in 2011, and the mission will get even closer to the planet in July and October, allowing for further study.

articles.author: DER SPIEGEL
articles.title: Missing submersible "Titan": "It's like finding a needle in a haystack" - DER SPIEGEL
articles.description: This article reports on the search for a mini-submarine, the "Titan", which has been missing since Sunday in the North Atlantic. The sub was carrying five people who were hoping to explore the wreckage of the Titanic. The search is being conducted by the Canadian and US coastguards, who are using ships and planes to try to locate the sub. The search is complicated by the fact that the sub is small and the North Atlantic is vast. The sub is equipped with a special cell made of carbon-fiber composite, which is designed to withstand the immense pressure at the depths where the Titanic lies.

articles.author: Space.com
articles.title: The loneliest monster black holes may also be the hungriest - Space.com
articles.description: New research suggests that supermassive black holes at the centers of galaxies in cosmic voids, where neighbors are rare and stellar nourishment is scarce, still manage to munch on material more often than their counterparts in more crowded areas of the galaxy. New observations found over 20,000 "hungry" black holes in lonely slices of the universe known as cosmic voids, show that these invisible beasts "snack" more often when there are fewer interacting neighbors to interrupt them. Cosmic voids are essentially "3D bubbles of space," some of which stretch over 500 million light-years across and contain just a handful of galaxies.

articles.author: Mirage News
articles.title: Tongan Volcano Plume Sets Lightning Record - Mirage News
articles.description: The eruption of the Hunga Volcano in 2022 created the highest lightning flash rates ever recorded on Earth, according to new research published in the journal Geophysical Research Letters. The volcanic plume created conditions for lightning at higher altitudes than normally seen, and lightning was observed at stratospheric altitudes where the air pressure is too low to support thunderstorm-like lightning. The lightning was detected by space-based optical sensors and global networks of ground-based radio antennas thousands of miles away. The research team found that the eruption produced 2,615 flashes per minute at its peak intensity, which lasted nearly five minutes.

articles.author: MIT News
articles.title: Professor Emeritus Roman Jackiw, “giant of theoretical physics,” dies at 83 - MIT News
articles.description: Eminent theoretical physicist Roman Jackiw, who was a member of the MIT physics community for 54 years, has died at the age of 83. Jackiw was a leader in the sophisticated use of quantum field theory to illuminate physical problems, and his influential work on topology and anomalies in quantum field theory underlies many aspects of theoretical physics today. He is renowned for his many fundamental contributions and discoveries in quantum and classical field theories, including the establishment of the presence of the famous Adler–Bell–Jackiw anomalies in quantum field theory.

articles.author: CNN en Español
articles.title: The North Atlantic suffers an "unprecedented" marine heat wave - CNN en Español
articles.description: The North Atlantic is experiencing an "exceptional" marine heatwave, with some areas seeing temperatures up to 5°C higher than usual, causing concern for marine life. The heatwave is "very exceptional" and "currently the most severe on Earth," according to Mika Rantanen, a researcher at the Finnish Meteorological Institute. The risks are high for marine species, such as fish, corals, and seagrasses, which have adapted to survive within certain temperature ranges. The warmer water can stress and even kill them. This heatwave is much worse than the worst predictions for the changing climate of the region, according to Richard Unsworth, an associate professor of Biosciences at the University of Plymouth.

articles.author: Tunisie Numérique
articles.title: Energy – Rising temperatures and storage drive down the price of European gas - Tunisie Numérique
articles.description: European gas prices, as measured by the Dutch Title Transfer Facility (TTF) futures contracts, have slightly increased by 2.2% to just above €30 per megawatt-hour, indicating that gas prices may have reached their lowest point for now. This drop in prices is due in part to warmer temperatures in the region, reducing demand for gas for heating, and high storage levels in Europe due to massive imports of liquefied natural gas, including from the US. However, experts warn that the market remains volatile and that sudden increases in demand could lead to price spikes. The EU has launched an international tender for group purchases of gas to replenish stocks before next winter and reduce dependence on Russia.
